[3
Date: Thu, 14 Jan 1999
>From "Chan Yow Cheong" <chanyowcheong@pacific.net.sg>
ProMED-mail Regional Moderator for Asia
Source: BERNAMA [Malaysia's National News Agency, 14 Jan 1999
The Japanese B Encephalitis (JE) outbreak in the country is under
control, Health Minister Datuk Chua Jui Meng said today. However,
preventive measures like fogging and anti-JE vaccinations were still
being conducted in the affected areas, he said.
"Those living near pig farms who contract fever will continue to be
admitted to the hospital for observation and treatment although they
may not be suffering from the JE disease," he told reporters after
visiting the Kuala Pilah Hospital, here.
The disease is spread from pigs to humans by the culex mosquito. Chua
said 34 people in Sikamat, Seremban, had been admitted to the
Seremban Hospital for checks and observation since the JE outbreak
in Kampung Wong Seng Chow, Sikamat and its surrounding areas.
Only two of them were confirmed to be suffering from the disease but
they had recovered and had been discharged. The three remaining
patients, who were not suffering from the disease, would be
discharged soon, he said.
Four people, including a 13-year-old girl, working in pig farms in
Kampung Wong Seng Chow, died between Jan 2 and 5, believed to be
victims of JE.
Chua said fogging [with insecticide would continue to be done in
Sikamat and Bukit Pelandok (Port Dickson) which had many pig farms.
He said that so far 1800 people in the two areas had been vaccinated
and he gave an assurance that there was ample supply of the vaccine.
